04331nam a22006015i 9780226540740DE-B159720191022022751.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||191022s2018    ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802265407407 a10.7208/97802265407402doi  a(DE-B1597)522571  a(OCoLC)1028552352  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 7aHIS0000002bisacsh04a621.388/872231 aGross, Benjamin, eauthor.14aThe TVs of Tomorrow :bHow RCA's Flat-Screen Dreams Led to the First LCDs /cBenjamin Gross. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2018] 4cÂ©2018  a1 online resource (288 p.) :b43 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aSynthesis00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tINTRODUCTION: A WORLD OF SCREENS -- t1. THE QUEST FOR MAGNALUX, 1951- 1956 -- t2. A FUMBLING PRELUDE, 1956- 1966 -- t3. SCATTERED ORIGINS, 1961- 1968 -- t4. DISRUPTIVE DISPLAYS, 1968- 1971 -- t5. THE CHANGING OF THE GUARD, 1969- 1976 -- tCONCLUSION: AN INVISIBLE MONUMENT -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tNOTES -- tBIBLIOGRAPHY -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn 1968 a team of scientists and engineers from RCA announced the creation of a new form of electronic display that relied upon an obscure set of materials known as liquid crystals. At a time when televisions utilized bulky cathode ray tubes to produce an image, these researchers demonstrated how liquid crystals could electronically control the passage of light. One day, they predicted, liquid crystal displays would find a home in clocks, calculators-and maybe even a television that could hang on the wall.   Half a century later, RCA's dreams have become a reality, and liquid crystals are the basis of a multibillion-dollar global industry. Yet the company responsible for producing the first LCDs was unable to capitalize upon its invention. In The TVs of Tomorrow, Benjamin Gross explains this contradiction by examining the history of flat-panel display research at RCA from the perspective of the chemists, physicists, electrical engineers, and technicians at the company's central laboratory in Princeton, New Jersey.   Drawing upon laboratory notebooks, internal reports, and interviews with key participants, Gross reconstructs the development of the LCD and situates it alongside other efforts to create a thin, lightweight replacement for the television picture tube. He shows how RCA researchers mobilized their technical expertise to secure support for their projects. He also highlights the challenges associated with the commercialization of liquid crystals at RCA and Optel-the RCA spin-off that ultimately manufactured the first LCD wristwatch. The TVs of Tomorrow is a detailed portrait of American innovation during the Cold War, which confirms that success in the electronics industry hinges upon input from both the laboratory and the boardroom.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 22. Okt 2019) 0aTelevisionxReceivers and reception. 4aLCD. 4aRCA. 4aRadio Corporation of America. 4aconsumer electronics. 4aflat panel displays. 4aindustrial research. 4ainnovation. 4aliquid crystal displays. 4aliquid crystals. 4atelevision. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018z978311063537940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226540740423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226540740.jpg  a978-3-11-063537-9  University of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018c2016d2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles